==Latin==

===Etymology 1===
From {{der|la|itc-pro|*is}}, from {{der|la|ine-pro|*Ã­s}}. Cognate with {{cog|osc|ğŒğŒ”ğŒğŒŠ}}, {{cog|xum|ğŒ„ğŒ“ğŒ„}}, and further with {{cog|lt|jis}}, {{cog|sla-pro|*jÑŒ}}.

====Pronunciation====
* {{la-IPA}}

====Pronoun====
{{la-det|is<irreg+>|cat2=pronouns|cat3=determiners}}

# {{lb|la|pronoun}} this or that man, woman or thing; [[he]], [[she]], [[it]], [[they]] {{gl|previously introduced}}
## {{n-g|Picks up the subject or object after an intervening clause, to avoid repeating the relative pronoun {{m|la|quÄ«}}, or substitutes [[fronting|syntactically fronted]] expressions}}
# {{lb|la|correlative}} [[that]]...[[which]]; [[he]], [[she]]...[[who]], [[it]]...[[that]]
## {{lb|la|anaphoric}} of such a [[nature]], [[degree]], [[kind]] {{gl|previously mentioned or implied}}
## {{lb|la|cataphoric}} the following; of the following [[nature]], [[degree]], [[kind]]
# {{lb|la|determiner}} [[this]] or [[that]] [man, woman or thing] {{q|as a noun phrase modifier}}
# {{lb|la|with|[[genus]]|+|nominative|or|[[modus|modÄ«]]|+|genitive}} [[such]] a, [[that]] [[sort]] of
#: {{uxi|la|'''eius'''modÄ« sermÅnÄ“s|talk '''of that''' kind}}
#* {{Q|la|Marcus Valerius Probus|Fragmenta|66|29|quote={{...}}'urbÄ«s' an 'urbÄ“s'. Nam cum '''id''' genus sÄ«s, quod videÅ, ut sine iactÅ«rÄ tuÄ peccÄ“s, nihil perdÄ“s utrum dÄ«xeris.|t={{...}}'urbÄ«s' or 'urbÄ“s'. For as far as I can see, you're '''the kind of man''' who doesn't lose sleep over his mistakes; as such you'll lose nothing whichever one you use.}}
# {{n-g|Substituting a clause.}}
#: {{uxi|la|quod '''eius''' fierÄ« possit|as far as [any '''of that''' is] possible}}
## {{n-g|As an [[internal accusative]]:}} for that [[reason]], on that [[account]]
##: {{uxi|la|'''id'''que gaudeÅ|and I'm glad '''about that'''}}
## {{n-g|Used in various prepositional phrases.}}

=====Usage notes=====
Latin ''is'' is an [[endophoric]] [[pronoun]] and [[determiner]], which may be employed either as an [[anaphora]] or as a [[cataphora]], meaning it serves as a reference to something preceding or following, respectively, in the text. Unlike a [[demonstrative]] such as {{m|la|ille}} or English [[this]], ''is'' does not have a [[deictic]] function, meaning it cannot point to a referent in the world, but only one named in the text; nor can it be used [[exophoric]]ally as a third-person pronoun such as English (s)[[he]] that refers to something not already defined in the [[context]] but presumed to be known or deducible by the addressee. Thus we see it used with first, second and third person.

The [[exophoric]] demonstratives/determiners in Latin are {{m|la|hic}} ([[proximal]], near the speaker), {{m|la|iste}} ([[medial]], near the listener), and {{m|la|ille}} ([[distal]], far from both). Note that Latin doesn't have any 3rd-person pronouns, using the aforementioned demonstratives in their place.

Oblique cases are rare in elevated poetry.

